<blue>1</blue><e13>STRASBOURG </e13>, Nov 29 -LRB- AFP -RRB- -- Three leading international organisations warned jointly Thursday -LSB- 29 November -RSB- that the international fight against terrorism should not be a pretext for the violation of human rights . <br><blue>2</blue>The <e2>Council </e2><e2>of </e2><e2>Europe </e2>, the <e10>Organization </e10><e10>for </e10><e10>Security </e10><e10>and </e10><e10>Cooperation </e10><e10>in </e10><e10>Europe </e10>-LRB- <e10>OSCE </e10>-RRB- and the <e15>UN </e15>High Commissioner for Human Rights said they were responding to recent `` worrying developments '' in some countries regarding human rights following the September 11 attacks . <br><blue>3</blue>`` While we recognize that the threat of terrorism requires specific measures , we call on all governments to refrain from any excessive steps which would violate fundamental freedoms and undermine legitimate dissent , '' a joint statement issued in <e13>Strasbourg </e13>, <e4>Geneva </e4>and <e18>Warsaw </e18>said . <br><blue>4</blue><e15>UN </e15>High Commissioner for Human Rights <e12>Mary </e12><e12>Robinson </e12>, <e17>Walter </e17><e17>Schwimmer </e17>, Secretary General of <e2><eC>the </eC></e2><e2><eC>Council </eC></e2><e2><eC>of </eC></e2><e2><eC>Europe </eC></e2>and Ambassador <e5>Gerard </e5><e5>Stoudmann </e5>of <e10><eC>the </eC></e10><e10><eC>OSCE </eC></e10><e10><eC>'s </eC></e10><e11>Office </e11><e11>for </e11><e11>Democratic </e11><e11>Institutions </e11><e11>and </e11><e11>Human </e11><e11>Rights </e11>said it was essential `` that states strictly adhere to their international obligations to uphold human rights and fundamental freedoms '' in the fight against terrorism . <br><blue>5</blue><e12>Robinson </e12>, a particularly critical voice in guarding against human rights abuses in the wake of the September 11 attacks , said Wednesday the war on terrorism was taking a heavy toll on civil liberties . <br><blue>6</blue>The statement comes two days after the British <e7>House </e7><e7>of </e7><e7>Commons </e7>passed emergency legislation allowing the detention of terrorist suspects without trial , and the killing of hundreds of <e14>Taliban </e14>inmates in a prison uprising in <e9>Mazar-i-Sharif </e9>in <e0><eC>northern </eC></e0><e0><eC>Afghanistan </eC></e0>earlier this week . <br><blue>7</blue>The killings prompted a call by London-based rights group <e1>Amnesty </e1><e1>International </e1>for an inquiry into the affair . <br><blue>8</blue>All three groups said it was essential that governments strike a balance between `` legitimate national security concerns and fundamental freedoms that is fully consistent with their international law commitments . '' <br><blue>9</blue>The statement listed what it said were essential rights that could not be hollowed out because of the fight against terrorism . <br><blue>10</blue>These were : the right to life , freedom of expression and religion and freedom from torture , while it also urged that the retroactive imposition of more severe penalties for crimes be avoided . <br><blue>11</blue>The <e16>United </e16><e16>States </e16>earlier this week hinted it may expand its war against terrorism beyond <e0>Afghanistan </e0>to <e8>Iraq </e8>, bringing swift criticism from both <e6>Germany </e6>and <e3>France </e3>, who called for restraint in the future of the military campaign . <br></div>
